":0,"fired":false,"rule_id":"USDPA-023","rule_version":"1.0.0"},{"elapsed_ms":0,"fired":false,"rule_id":"USDPA-024","rule_version":"1.0.0"},{"elapsed_ms":0,"fired":false,"rule_id":"USDPA-025","rule_version":"1.0.0"}],"findings":[{"description":"Used but not defined: Customer Data.","document_position":6396,"excerpt":{"end_offset":6409,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":6396,"text":"Customer Data"},"explanation":"Title-Case phrases in a contract usually signal a defined term. When they aren't defined, readers must guess at the intended meaning. Either define them or use lowercase if the term is intended in its ordinary sense.","id":"STRUCT-006-s1-6396","recommendation":"Add a definition for each genuinely defined term, or change the casing if the phrase is being used in its ordinary sense.","rule_id":"STRUCT-006","rule_version":"1.1.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"Undefined Title-Case terms: 1"},{"description":"set forth in Schedule A — Schedule A is not attached to the document.","document_position":5264,"excerpt":{"end_offset":5287,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":5264,"text":" times, and service credit schedule, is set forth in Schedule A, attached hereto and incorporated herein by reference."},"explanation":"The agreement refers to an exhibit / schedule / attachment as the source of operative terms, but the referenced exhibit is missing or empty. The operative terms are therefore not in the contract. If the exhibit is meant to be supplied later, that later supplement is a new contractual document and should be governed by an amendment process.","id":"STRUCT-016-s1-5264","recommendation":"Attach a substantive Schedule A before execution, or remove the reference. If the exhibit is genuinely intended to be filled in later, mark it 'to be agreed' and add a process: who proposes, by when, what happens if the parties cannot agree.","rule_id":"STRUCT-016","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"Schedule A referenced but missing"},{"description":"Schedule A is referenced but not attached to the document.","document_position":5277,"excerpt":{"end_offset":5287,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":5277,"text":"Schedule A"},"explanation":"The agreement refers to an exhibit, schedule, annex, appendix, or attachment that is not present in the document. If the referenced material carries operative terms, those terms are missing from the contract. (In folder mode, a referenced attachment that is a sibling file is reconciled before this is reported.) This is an internal-consistency check, not an assertion that the attachment is legally required.","id":"STRUCT-018-s1-5277","recommendation":"Attach each referenced item (Schedule A) before execution, or remove the reference if it is no longer needed. Reconcile every cross-reference to a present attachment as part of the closing checklist.","rule_id":"STRUCT-018","rule_version":"1.1.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"Referenced attachment not present: 1"},{"description":"The contract references data but does not separately allocate data ownership.","document_position":6396,"excerpt":{"end_offset":6409,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":6396,"text":"13. Data Return. On termination or expiration of this Agreement, Vendor shall within thirty (30) days return all Customer Data in a machine-readable format and then delete or destroy all remaining copies of Customer Data from Vendor's syste"},"explanation":"IP and data ownership are different. For SaaS, the customer typically owns its data; the vendor typically owns usage analytics. Address each explicitly.","id":"IPDATA-004-s1-6396","rule_id":"IPDATA-004","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Data ownership not separately addressed"},{"description":"No indemnification covering breach of confidentiality was found.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"Confidentiality breaches often produce damages that are difficult to quantify; indemnification anchors the remedy.","id":"MSA-003-s1-0","recommendation":"Add an indemnity for damages arising from breach of confidentiality obligations.","rule_id":"MSA-003","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-commercial-drafting-baseline-confidentiality-indemnity","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"Commercial drafting baseline — confidentiality indemnity","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/ucc"}],"title":"Confidentiality breach indemnity missing"},{"description":"Indemnification appears to be excluded from the aggregate liability cap.","document_position":4361,"excerpt":{"end_offset":4454,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":4361,"text":"8. Limitation of Liability. (a) Aggregate Liability Cap. EACH PARTY'S AGGREGATE LIABILITY TO THE OTHER FOR ALL CLAIMS ARISING OUT OF OR RELATED TO THIS AGREEMENT SHALL NOT EXCEED THE TOTAL FEES PAID OR PAYABLE BY CUSTOMER IN THE TWELVE (12) MONTHS IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING THE CLAIM."},"explanation":"Whether indemnification falls inside or outside the cap is the most contested cap-carve-out term. The report surfaces it for explicit review.","id":"MSA-005-s1-4361","recommendation":"Confirm intent: keep indemnity inside the cap (lower vendor exposure), put it outside (higher customer protection), or place it under a supercap (compromise).","rule_id":"MSA-005","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-commercial-drafting-baseline-indemnity-cap-interaction","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"Commercial drafting baseline — indemnity / cap interaction","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/ucc"}],"title":"Indemnification excluded from liability cap"},{"description":"No termination-on-insolvency clause was found.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"11 U.S.C. § 365 makes pure ipso-facto clauses unenforceable in some scenarios, but the contract should still anchor the parties' intent.","id":"MSA-019-s1-0","recommendation":"Add: termination on filing for bankruptcy, appointment of receiver, or assignment for the benefit of creditors.","rule_id":"MSA-019","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-11-u-s-c-365-bankruptcy-considerations","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"11 U.S.C. § 365 — Bankruptcy considerations","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/11/365"}],"title":"Termination for bankruptcy / insolvency missing"},{"description":"No clause was found addressing AI / generative AI usage by the vendor in service delivery.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"Increasingly the contract should disclose AI use, training data, and IP ownership of outputs (see the §49 AI Addendum playbook for the deep check).","id":"MSA-028-s1-0","recommendation":"Add a clause disclosing whether AI is used, naming material AI subprocessors, and addressing IP in outputs.","rule_id":"MSA-028","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-nist-ai-rmf-transparency-baseline","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"NIST AI RMF — transparency baseline","source_url":"https://www.nist.gov/itl/ai-risk-management-framework"}],"title":"AI usage clause missing"},{"description":"Exclusive / limited remedy language is present but no UCC § 2-719(2) fail-of-essential-purpose escape was found.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"UCC § 2-719(2) preserves alternative remedies when a limited remedy fails of its essential purpose — anchoring this protects the customer from a remedy gap.","id":"MSA-030-s1-0","recommendation":"Add: 'if the limited remedy is found to fail of its essential purpose, the customer's other remedies under this Agreement and applicable law remain available.'","rule_id":"MSA-030","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-u-c-c-2-719-2-","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"U.C.C. § 2-719(2)","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/ucc/2/2-719"}],"title":"UCC § 2-719 limited-remedy escape missing"},{"description":"The indemnifying party shall not settle any claim that imposes liability on the indemnified party without the indemnifie | EACH PARTY'S AGGREGATE LIABILITY TO THE OTHER FOR ALL CLAIMS ARISING OUT OF OR RELATED TO THIS AGREEMENT SHALL NOT EXCEE | The aggregate cap shall not apply to: (i) breach of confidentiality obligations; (ii) either party's indemnification obl","document_position":3897,"excerpt":{"end_offset":4050,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":3897,"text":"The indemnifying party shall not settle any claim that imposes liability on the indemnified party without the indemnified party's prior written consent."},"explanation":"Negative covenants restrict what a party may do. Surfacing them collectively makes it easier to check they are intended and consistent with the overall deal.","id":"OBLI-005-s1-3897","rule_id":"OBLI-005","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Negative covenants: 3"},{"description":"INCIDENTAL, SPECIAL, EXEMPLARY, OR CONSEQUENTIAL DAMAGES","document_position":4669,"excerpt":{"end_offset":4725,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":4669,"text":"8. Limitation of Liability. (a) Aggregate Liability Cap. EACH PARTY'S AGGREGATE LIABILITY TO THE OTHER FOR ALL CLAIMS ARISING OUT OF OR RELATED TO THIS AGREEMENT SHALL NOT EXCEED THE TOTAL FEES PAID OR PAYABLE BY CUSTOMER IN THE TWELVE (12)"},"explanation":"A waiver of consequential, special, incidental, and punitive damages is standard in commercial contracts. The waiver should be mutual unless deliberately asymmetric.","id":"RISK-007-s1-4669","rule_id":"RISK-007","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Consequential damages waiver present"},{"description":"commercial general liability insurance with limits of at least $1,000,000","document_position":4860,"excerpt":{"end_offset":4933,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":4860,"text":"9. Insurance. During the term, Vendor shall maintain commercial general liability insurance with limits of at least $1,000,000 per occurrence and $2,000,000 in the aggregate, and professional liability insurance with limits of at least $1,000,000 per occurrence."},"explanation":"Insurance levels should match the deal size and risk. Common minimums are $1M per occurrence CGL and $2M E&O for services contracts.","id":"RISK-010-s1-4860","rule_id":"RISK-010","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Insurance requirements stated"},{"description":"Indemnity clause appears to be missing: settlement consent.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"7. Mutual Indemnification. (a) Vendor Indemnification. Vendor shall indemnify, defend, and hold harmless Customer from any third-party claim arising from: (i) infringement of a third-party intellectual property right by the deliverables; (ii) gross negligence or willful misconduc"},"explanation":"A complete indemnity clause specifies (a) the timeline and form for notice of a claim, (b) which party controls defense, and (c) whether settlement requires consent.","id":"RISK-011-s1-0","rule_id":"RISK-011","rule_version":"1.3.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Indemnity procedural elements missing: settlement consent"},{"description":"Force Majeure","document_position":5787,"excerpt":{"end_offset":5800,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":5787,"text":"12. Force Majeure. Neither party shall be liable for any delay or failure to perform its obligations under this Agreement to the extent such delay or failure is caused by circumstances beyond such party's reasonable control, including acts of God, war, terrorism, strikes, governm"},"explanation":"Force-majeure clauses excuse performance during specified events beyond a party's control. Scope varies widely; pandemics, supply-chain disruption, and government action are common modern additions.","id":"RISK-013-s1-5787","rule_id":"RISK-013","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Force majeure clause present"},{"description":"confidentiality obligations shall survive termination for three (3) year","document_position":2392,"excerpt":{"end_offset":2464,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":2392,"text":"5. Confidentiality. Each party (as \"Receiving Party\") shall hold in strict confidence all non-public information of the other party (as \"Disclosing Party\") designated as confidential or that reasonably should be understood to be confidentia"},"explanation":"Typical post-termination confidentiality terms run 3–5 years for general information, with a perpetual duty for trade secrets. Verify the term matches the sensitivity of the information.","id":"RISK-014-s1-2392","rule_id":"RISK-014","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Confidentiality term length stated"},{"description":"The following defined terms are never used outside their definition: Vendor Background IP.","document_position":1412,"excerpt":{"end_offset":1436,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":1412,"text":"Vendor Background IP"},"explanation":"Defined terms that are not used downstream may be inherited from a template and obsolete. They clutter the contract and can confuse readers; either delete them or use them where intended.","id":"STRUCT-005-s1-1412","recommendation":"Review each unused term and either delete it or wire it into the relevant clause.","rule_id":"STRUCT-005","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Defined terms with no uses: 1"},{"description":"Provisions are stated to survive termination.","document_position":2426,"excerpt":{"end_offset":2445,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":2426,"text":"5. Confidentiality. Each party (as \"Receiving Party\") shall hold in strict confidence all non-public information of the other party (as \"Disclosing Party\") designated as confidential or that reasonably should be understood to be confidentia"},"explanation":"A survival clause names the obligations that outlast termination — typically confidentiality, indemnity, payment obligations accrued before termination, and choice of law.","id":"TEMP-006-s1-2426","rule_id":"TEMP-006","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Survival clause present"}],"playbook_id":"msa-vendor-deep","playbook_match_confidence":1,"playbook_match_reasoning":"forced via sidecar to msa-vendor-deep","result_hash":"43d311c346789332b6d60b9b97df685bd355b00911dcd4afc851949031cd44a1","source_file":{"name":"msa-vendor-deep-missing-bankruptcy-termination-fail.txt","sha256":"47f3664f5cef8f0ff50168cb0179fb9cdf5f1d9e722f8d84847ddffbeb2124b2","size_bytes":1},"version":"9.41.0"}